TY  - JOUR
T1  - Which GARCH Model for Option Valuation?
AU  - Christoffersen, Peter
AU  - Jacobs, Kris
Y1  - 2004/09/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1040.0276
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1040.0276
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1204
EP  - 1221
VL  - 50
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Characterizing asset return dynamics using volatility models is an important part of empirical finance. The existing literature on GARCH models favors some rather complex volatility specifications whose relative performance is usually assessed through their likelihood based on a time series of asset returns. This paper compares a range of GARCH models along a different dimension, using option prices and returns under the risk-neutral as well as the physical probability measure. We judge the relative performance of various models by evaluating an objective function based on option prices. In contrast with returns-based inference, we find that our option-based objective function favors a relatively parsimonious model. Specifically, when evaluated out-of-sample, our analysis favors a model that, besides volatility clustering, only allows for a standard leverage effect.
AB  - Characterizing asset return dynamics using volatility models is an important part of empirical finance. The existing literature on GARCH models favors some rather complex volatility specifications whose relative performance is usually assessed through their likelihood based on a time series of asset returns. This paper compares a range of GARCH models along a different dimension, using option prices and returns under the risk-neutral as well as the physical probability measure. We judge the relative performance of various models by evaluating an objective function based on option prices. In contrast with returns-based inference, we find that our option-based objective function favors a relatively parsimonious model. Specifically, when evaluated out-of-sample, our analysis favors a model that, besides volatility clustering, only allows for a standard leverage effect.
